Key Findings:
Raw Performance: GLM marginally outperformed TabPFN on discrimination (0.5991 vs 0.5929 ROC AUC). This is surprising newer, more complex models did not universally win. On this well-structured lapse problem with primarily additive effects, simpler methods proved competitive. This tells us something important: on this dataset, the underlying lapse patterns are straightforward enough that traditional actuarial models compete effectively with modern foundation models.
Calibration Quality: While raw discrimination was similar, TabPFN's probability estimates were significantly overconfident a common characteristic of neural networks. Post-hoc isotonic calibration improved TabPFN's Brier score by +0.87% to 0.1080, outperforming the GLM's raw calibration (0.1098). This demonstrates a genuine business advantage for actuarial applications where probability accuracy directly impacts pricing, reserving, and capital decisions.
Computational Trade-off: GLM training took 0.04s; TabPFN required 1.89s (remote API overhead). For annual recalibration workflows, this is negligible. For production scoring at scale, GLM's latency advantage may matter.
Across all models, predictive performance was modest. Using the cleaned dataset, the GLM achieved a test AUC of approximately 0.63, with TabPFN delivering a near-identical result. When applied to the raw dataset (containing many sparse categorical levels and ungrouped variables) both models again produced very similar AUC values, with no material advantage for TabPFN. These results suggest that in this setting, most of the predictive signal is already captured by a relatively simple additive structure.
One particular point of interest was how each model behaves across different decision thresholds. As lapses are a relatively rare event, the dataset is inherently imbalanced and so accuracy as a metric would be misleading (with high accuracy achievable simply by predicting non-lapse). Instead, metrics such as recall, precision and F1 score provide a more informative view. For both models, optimal F1 scores were achieved at relatively low probability cutoffs (around 0.10 - 0.15), reflecting the need to trade off false positives against missed lapses.
Interestingly, TabPFN’s ability to operate directly on the raw dataset did not translate into improved predictive power over the GLM. While the model handled sparse categories and mixed feature types without difficulty, its performance closely mirrored that of the GLM once basic actuarial data preparation had been applied. This finding is consistent with the exploratory analysis presented earlier: many of the strongest drivers of lapse in this dataset (such as policyholder age, payment frequency and policy tenure) exhibit smooth, monotonic effects that are well aligned with a logistic regression framework.
Where TabPFN Adds Value
Probability Calibration: For insurance professionals, the distinction between raw prediction power and calibration quality is critical. A poorly calibrated model might predict 20% lapse probability when the true rate is actually 15%. Over thousands of policies, these small errors compound into mispricing, inadequate reserves, and capital misallocation. After isotonic adjustment, TabPFN delivers superior calibrated probabilities (Brier improvement +0.87%), demonstrating meaningful value for probability-critical actuarial applications.
Setup Simplicity: TabPFN requires no hyperparameter tuning, no grid search, no cross-validation, no architecture searching. All models in this study received identical preprocessing. TabPFN's advantage lies in making reliable predictions without the manual model configuration required by traditional approaches.
Why Calibration Matters More Than Raw Power: The Brier Score measures calibration quality and how well predicted probabilities match observed outcomes. Our analysis shows:
Raw TabPFN: 0.1108
Calibrated TabPFN (isotonic): 0.1080 (+0.87% improvement)
GLM: 0.1098
Once calibrated, TabPFN outperforms the GLM specifically where it matters most for actuarial work: probability accuracy.
Critical Trade-Offs
Interpretability: GLM coefficients directly explain driver effects on lapse, a feature highly valued in regulated actuarial practice. TabPFN, as a black-box neural network, requires post-hoc explanation techniques (SHAP, feature importance) to justify predictions to regulators and stakeholders. This governance cost is substantial in practice.
Raw Prediction Power: On this dataset, both models are equivalent (~59% ROC AUC). No single method universally dominates. The "best" model depends on your specific priorities.
Inference Speed: GLM prediction latency is 0.01s; TabPFN via remote API is 7.6s. For quote-to-cash workflows requiring real-time scoring, this matters. For batch recalibration, it's negligible.
Optimization Experiments
We tested post-hoc optimization strategies to further improve TabPFN without GPU-based weight retraining:
Ensemble Bagging: Combining three TabPFN models via bootstrap → degraded performance (TabPFN already extracts available signal effectively)
Calibration Comparison: Isotonic vs Platt scaling → Isotonic won (+0.87% vs +0.45% Brier improvement)
Feature Engineering + Calibration: Combined approach → +1.66% additional improvement
Key Lesson: Small, targeted improvements in calibration often outweigh attempts at raw prediction power. This aligns with actuarial wisdom: probability accuracy directly drives business value.
Practical Business Impact
To understand what these metrics mean in dollars, consider a portfolio of 100,000 policies with 13,000 expected lapses:
Pricing Impact: If a model's calibrated probability is 15% but actual lapse rate is 20%, the insurer underprices by 5 percentage points. Over 13,000 lapses, this compounds into lost premium revenue. TabPFN's calibration advantage (+0.87% Brier improvement) translates to more accurate probability estimates that reduce systematic mispricing across the portfolio.
Capital Allocation: Actuarial reserves must account for claim uncertainty. Poor probability calibration inflates or deflates reserves, misallocating scarce capital. The GLM and calibrated TabPFN's near-identical Brier scores (0.1098 vs 0.1080) mean both can drive adequate reserve setting. However, TabPFN's slight edge is valuable for edge cases and tail risk assessment.
Production Implementation: The choice between GLM and TabPFN depends on operational constraints:
Batch Scoring (Annual/Quarterly Recalibration): TabPFN's 1.89s fit time is negligible. Calibration quality wins. Deploy calibrated TabPFN.
Real-Time Quote Systems: GLM's 0.04s inference latency is critical; TabPFN's API dependency introduces unacceptable latency. Deploy GLM.
Hybrid Approach (Recommended): Use GLM for quote systems (speed), TabPFN for reserving models (calibration). Both feed into ensemble pricing logic.
