Conclusion
TabPFN is not a replacement for classical methods—it's a complementary tool. Our comprehensive evaluation demonstrates:
GLM Advantages:
Speed (0.04s training)
Interpretability (direct coefficients)
Raw discrimination performance (0.5991 ROC AUC)
TabPFN Advantages:
Calibration quality (0.1080 Brier when calibrated)
Zero hyperparameter tuning
Robustness across diverse data distributions
For Practitioners: Choose by priority, not by hype. If probability accuracy matters most (as it does in reserving and capital models), calibrated TabPFN wins. If interpretability and speed are paramount, the GLM remains hard to beat.
The Optimal Strategy:
Use GLM for regulatory approval and stakeholder transparency
Use calibrated TabPFN for probability-critical pricing models
Monitor both for production stability
There is still plenty of life in the old GLM yet. Modern foundation models like TabPFN enrich the actuarial toolkit without rendering classical approaches obsolete. The future of actuarial modelling lies not in choosing one method, but in deploying both intelligently.
Having set out to explore if TabPFN can deliver tangible benefits over a traditional actuarial GLM, we find the answer is not always! Examining a realistic lapse-modelling context using the eudirectlapse dataset, we find little evidence that TabPFN materially outperforms a carefully specified logistic regression model, whether applied to cleaned or raw data. In this case, the GLM appears to capture most of the available predictive signal.
Does this mean that TabPFN is limited? Not necessarily so, rather our analysis highlights an important practical insight: when the underlying relationships are largely additive, monotonic and well understood, classical actuarial models remain highly competitive. The value of TabPFN may lie elsewhere, likely in settings with more complex interactions, smaller datasets, or where a quick answer without the need for extensive feature engineering is desirable. From an actuarial perspective, TabPFN’s most compelling contribution may therefore be workflow efficiency rather than outright predictive dominance. The ability to obtain reasonable predictions without extensive preprocessing, hyperparameter tuning or model selection is attractive, particularly in exploratory or time-constrained settings. The transparency, interpretability and regulatory familiarity of GLMs remain powerful advantages, although the integration of TabPFN with Shapley values may well come to challenge this.
In summary we have come to realise that the right method for the task is often dataset dependent. Old-fashioned data visualisation and exploration can be a helpful safeguard against the temptation to get carried away with complex methodologies. While using a sledgehammer to crack a walnut can be tremendous fun, we should aim for the simplest solution that fits the problem. Ultimately, our results reinforce a reassuring message for practitioners: while new modelling tools continue to expand our toolkit, there is still plenty of life in the old GLM yet!

Appendix A: Detailed Methodology
Data Preparation: eudirectlapse dataset (23,060 policies, 18 features, ~13% lapse rate) split 70/30 with stratification (seed 45). All models received identical preprocessing: ordinal encoding for categorical variables, standardization for numerical features. This ensures fair comparison where performance differences reflect each model's inherent capabilities.

Competing Models:

Logistic Regression (GLM): Scikit-learn, default parameters
TabPFN v2.5: Client API, zero manual tuning
CatBoost: Categorical-optimized gradient boosting, defaults
RandomForest: 100 trees, defaults
XGBoost: Industry-standard gradient boosting, defaults

Evaluation Metrics:
ROC AUC: Discrimination ability (how well the model ranks positives above negatives). Range: 0.5 (random) to 1.0 (perfect). GLM's 0.5991 means it ranks a random lapse ~60% higher than a random non-lapse.
PR AUC: Precision-Recall AUC (emphasizes minority class performance, more informative for imbalanced data like our ~13% lapse rate). More conservative than ROC AUC for imbalanced problems.
Brier Score: Calibration quality (mean squared difference between predicted probability and actual outcome; lower is better). Directly relevant to actuarial applications where probability accuracy drives pricing and reserving.

Why Brier Score Matters Most: Insurance applications require accurate probability estimates. A model predicting 15% lapse probability when actual is 20% systematically underprices. Over a 100,000-policy portfolio with 13,000 expected lapses, this compounds into millions in mispricing. Brier score captures this directly.

Calibration Analysis: Post-hoc isotonic regression applied to TabPFN predictions. Isotonic (non-parametric, makes no distributional assumptions) outperformed Platt scaling (+0.87% vs +0.45% Brier improvement). Applied to GLM predictions for fairness comparison, confirming that TabPFN benefits more from post-calibration because neural networks tend toward overconfidence.

Calibration Analysis: Post-hoc isotonic regression applied to TabPFN predictions. Isotonic (non-parametric, makes no distributional assumptions) outperformed Platt scaling (+0.87% vs +0.45% Brier improvement). Applied to GLM predictions for fairness comparison, confirming that TabPFN benefits more from post-calibration.

Reproducibility: Fixed random seeds (45 for train/test split, 943321 for stochastic components). All code runnable end-to-end with Python 3.8+, scikit-learn ≥1.0, TabPFN client API.

Appendix B: How TabPFN Works
TabPFN represents a paradigm shift in tabular prediction. Rather than being trained on a single dataset, TabPFN is pre-trained on millions of synthetically generated tabular datasets to learn general prediction strategies—essentially learning "how to solve tabular problems in general."

In-Context Learning: During pre-training, TabPFN is exposed to synthetic datasets capturing diverse data-generating processes: non-linear relationships, missing values, categorical variables, noise, class imbalance, and high-dimensional feature spaces. When you apply TabPFN to new data, you provide the full training sample as context. The model processes this in a single forward pass and generates predictions—no hyperparameter tuning, no cross-validation, no architecture search.

Version 2.5 Improvements:

Deeper transformer architectures for better feature interaction modeling
Richer synthetic training priors reflecting realistic data distributions
Inference-time optimizations for speed
Extended to datasets up to 50,000 rows with mixed feature types

Practical Advantages: No hyperparameter tuning eliminates lengthy grid search workflows; works with raw data requiring only standard preprocessing; robustness via pre-training on diverse data; naturally generates probability estimates aligned with uncertainty.

Tradeoffs: Remote API latency (~2 seconds), black-box predictions requiring post-hoc explanation, cannot adjust model for domain constraints or fairness objectives after training.
